<paragraph blockId="8.[812,1422,934,1445]" pageId="8" pageNumber="193">
The only representative of this genus in the Volga River drainage (
<bibRefCitation author="Bogutskaya NG &amp; Coad BW" box="[990,1297,1087,1111]" pageId="8" pageNumber="193" pagination="126 - 173" refId="ref15173" refString="Bogutskaya NG, Coad BW (2009) A review of vertebral and fin-ray counts in the genus Alburnoides (Teleostei: Cyprinidae) with a description of six new species. Zoosystematica Rossica 18 (1): 126 - 173." type="journal article" year="2009">Bogutskaya and Coad 2009</bibRefCitation>
), identified by a small black spot on each side of lateral line pore and 12–17 branched anal-fin rays. Although included in the Russian Red List since 2001 (
<bibRefCitation author="Danilov-Danilyan VI" box="[1146,1408,1187,1211]" pageId="8" pageNumber="193" refId="ref14842" refString="Danilov-Danilyan VI (2001) Krasnaya kniga Rossiiskoi Federatsii (Zhivotnye) [Russian Red List for animal species]. AST Astrel', Moscow, 862 pp." type="book" year="2001">Danilov-Danilyan 2001</bibRefCitation>
), it is still rather abundant in the Moksha River (
<bibRefCitation author="Ruchin AB &amp; Kozhara AV &amp; Levin BA &amp; Baklanov MA &amp; Zakharov VYu &amp; Artaev ON" pageId="8" pageNumber="193" pagination="631 - 638" refId="ref16552" refString="Ruchin AB, Kozhara AV, Levin BA, Baklanov MA, Zakharov VYu, Artaev ON (2007) On the distribution of riffle minnow Alburnoides bipunctatus (Cyprinidae) in the Volga Basin. Journal of Ichthyology 47 (8): 631 - 638. https: // doi. org / 10.1134 / S 0032945207080097" type="journal article" year="2007">Ruchin et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ruchin AB &amp; Shlyakhtin GV &amp; Artaev ON" box="[915,973,1254,1278]" pageId="8" pageNumber="193" pagination="194 - 198" refId="ref16512" refString="Ruchin AB, Shlyakhtin GV, Artaev ON (2009) Species composition and quantitative representation of fishes in biotopes with the riffle minnow Alburnoides bipunctatus. Russian Journal of Ecology 40 (3): 194 - 198." type="journal article" year="2009">2009</bibRefCitation>
). This species lives only in rivers, and its abundance in the Moksha drainage increases forward to downstream (12.8% in the river on a distance of 
<quantity box="[1352,1421,1320,1345]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="8" pageNumber="193" unit="km" value="26.0">26 km</quantity>
from the source up to 38.5% in the river from 
<quantity metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.005" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.01" pageId="8" pageNumber="193" unit="km" value="400.5" valueMax="500.0" valueMin="301.0">301 to 500 km</quantity>
from the source); more abundant (35.8%) in the portion between 26 and 
<quantity box="[1071,1152,1421,1445]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="193" unit="km" value="100.0">100 km</quantity>
from the source of river.
</paragraph>
